4 Kriging prediction

The kriging approach is a method for modeling and smoothing a set of stochastic observations and make predictions for new unobserved input locations (input values). The kriging approach bases the accurate generalization (prediction) of data on the correlation structure among the data. The correlation strucutre of the data is defined by the semivariogram function.

4.1 Mean and variance kriging prediction

Given a set of sample observations \(\boldsymbol{y}= \{y(s_i)\}\) from a spatial stochastic process at the spatial locations \(s_i\), with \(i=1,\dots,n\) location indices. A kriging prediction of the stochastic process at a unobserved arbitrary spatial location \(s_0\) is the lineal combination of the observed values at the sample locations:

\[\begin{align*} \hat{y}(s_0)= \sum_{i=1}^n \lambda_i y(s_i), \end{align*}\]

where the weights \(\lambda_1,\dots,\lambda_n\) are those that minimize the mean squared error

\[\begin{align*} E[(y(s_0) - \hat{y}(s_0)^2], \end{align*}\]

under the constraint of \(\sum_{i=1}^n \lambda_i=1\) that, jointly with the stationarity of the mean process, guarantees an unbiassed predictor. We can distinguish the simple kriging, or kriging without a global tendency, and the universal kriging, or kriging with a global tendency. In the simple kriging the mean of the process is considered as a constant function (null or constant global tendency). In the universal kriging the mean of the process is considered as a linear regression function of input values (global tendency function), such as:

\[\begin{align*} \mu(s_i) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_1(s_i) + \cdots + \beta_p x_p(s_i) = \boldsymbol{\beta} \boldsymbol{x}(s_i), \end{align*}\]

where \(\boldsymbol{x}(s_i)=(1,x_1(s_i),\dots, x_p(s_i))^\top\) is the vector with the \(p\) input values associated to spatial location \(s_i\) and \(\boldsymbol{\beta}=(\beta_0,\beta_1,\dots, \beta_p)\) is the vector with the linear coefficients.

The solution to this optimization problem is for the estimated mean, following Cressie (1993):

\[\begin{align*} \hat{y}(s_0) = [\boldsymbol{\gamma} + X(X^\top \Gamma^{-1} X)(\boldsymbol{x}(s_0) - X^\top \Gamma^{-1} \boldsymbol{\gamma})]^\top \Gamma^{-1} \boldsymbol{y}, \end{align*}\]

and for the estimated variance:

\[\begin{align*} \sigma^2_s = \boldsymbol{\gamma}^\top \Gamma^{-1} \boldsymbol{\gamma} - \frac{(\boldsymbol{I}^\top \Gamma^{-1} \boldsymbol{\gamma} - 1)^2}{\boldsymbol{I}^\top \Gamma^{-1} \boldsymbol{I}}, \end{align*}\]

where \(X=[\boldsymbol{x}(s_1) \; \cdots \; \boldsymbol{x}(s_i) \; \cdots \; \boldsymbol{x}(s_n)]^\top \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times p}\) is the matrix with the \(p\) input values for the \(n\) sample observations and \(\boldsymbol{x}(s_0)=(x_1(s_0),\dots,x_p(s_0))^\top\) is the vector with the \(p\) input values for the location \(s_0\). In the vector \(\boldsymbol{\gamma}=(\gamma(|s_1-s_0|),\dots,\gamma(|s_n-s_0|))^\top\) and matrix \(\Gamma \in \mathbb{R}^{n\times n}\) with element \(\Gamma_{(i,j)}=\gamma(|s_i-s_j|)\), \(\gamma\) represents the semivariogram function as a function of the euclidean distance between the sample locations \(s_i\) and \(s_j\) (\(i,j=1,\dots,n\)).

4.2 Semivariogram function

The spatial semivariogram function \(\gamma\) defines the correlation structure among observed values of a stationary stochastic process, determining the relationships between the observations at different spatial locations. A stochastic process is said to be stationary when the covariance between two observations is a function of the difference of spatial locations:

\[\begin{align*} \mathrm{cov}(y(s_i),y(s_j)) = f(s_i - s_j), \end{align*}\]

and isotropic when is a function of the norm between two spatial locations:

\[\begin{align*} \mathrm{cov}(y(s_i),y(s_j)) = f(|s_i - s_j|) = f(h), \end{align*}\]

with \(h=|s_i - s_j|\). A stationary and isotropic spatial semivariogram funcion is the semivariance of the increments of the observations of the stochastic process:

\[\begin{align*} \gamma(h)=\frac{1}{2} \mathrm{var}(y(s + h) - y(s)), \tag{4.1} \end{align*}\]

where \(s\) represents an arbitrary spatial location and \(h\) the spatial distance between two arbitrary spatial locations.

From classical geostatistics the semivariogram needs to be estimated beforehand from the sample observations. The first step is to obtain the empirical semivariogram, and secondly to adjust an analytical function for the semivariogram function over the empirical variogram.

4.2.1 Empirical semivariogram

The empirical variagram consists in computing the semivariances, according the equation (4.1), for the different spatial distances \(h > 0\) among spatial locations, as follows:

\[\begin{align*} \gamma(h)=\frac{1}{2} \frac{1}{||N(h)||} \sum_{i,j \in N(h)}(y(s_i) - y(s_j)), \end{align*}\]

where \(N(h)= \{\{s_i, s_j\} : |s_i s_j| = h,\;\: i,j = 1,\dots,n\}\) is the set of pairs of spatial locations separated by the distance \(h\), and \(||N(h)||\) represents the cardinality of \(N(h)\). In practice, it is impossible to find several pairs of locations separated by all the possible distances \(h\). Then, it is commonly adressed by partitioning the spectrum of distances into several intervals, and a estimate of the semivariance is obtained for each interval. The resulting graph is called the empirical variogram. Regarding the choice of the number of intervals of the partition, it should be considered that too few intervals could give rise to overly smoothed semivariograms and that many intervals with few observations each could give rise to highly wiggly semivariograms where the dominant variability is that of the estimator error. suggests at least 30 pairs of observations in each interval as a reasonable and practical number.

4.2.2 Semivariogram function

The empirical semivariogram provides a set of estimation values of the semivariogram function \(\gamma(\cdot)\) for some distances. With this information, an analytical function for the semivariogram must be obtained. A valid semivariogram function must meet the following restrictions: \(\gamma(0) \geq 0\), \(\gamma(h) \leq \sigma^2\), \(\forall h \geq 0\), where \(\sigma^2\) is the variance of a single observation \(\mathrm{var}(y(s_i))=\sigma^2\), \(\forall s_i\), and be conditionally negative definite that ensures that the variance of a predicted value is non-negative .

Some of the most common families of parametric functions which ensure the property of conditionally negative definite for the semivariogram \(\gamma(\cdot)\) are the following:

\[\begin{align*} \text{Pure nugget effect:} & \hspace{1cm} \gamma(h) = \tau^2, \hspace{5mm} \forall h > 0 \\[2mm] \text{Funcion exponencial:} & \hspace{1cm} \gamma(h) = \tau^2 + (\sigma^2 \tau^2)\left(1-e^{-3\frac{h}{\phi}}\right), \hspace{5mm} \forall h > 0 \\[2mm] \text{Funcion gaussiana:} & \hspace{1cm} \gamma(h) = \tau^2 + (\sigma^2 \tau^2)\left(1-e^{-3(\frac{h}{\phi})^2}\right), \hspace{5mm} \forall h > 0 \\[2mm] \text{Funcion esferica:} & \hspace{1cm} \gamma(h) = \left\{ \begin{array}{cc} \tau^2 + (\sigma^2 \tau^2)\left( \frac{3h}{2\phi} - \frac{h^3}{2\phi^3}\right),& \hspace{5mm} 0 < h > 0\\ \sigma^2,& \hspace{5mm} h \geq \phi\\ \end{array} \right.\\[2mm] \text{Funcion Matern:} & \hspace{1cm} \gamma_\kappa(h) = \tau^2 + (\sigma^2 \tau^2)\left(1- \frac{(2\sqrt{\kappa} h / \phi)^\kappa}{2^{\kappa-1} \Gamma(\kappa)} K_\kappa \left(\frac{2\sqrt{\kappa}h}{\phi}\right) \right), \hspace{5mm} \forall \tau > 0,\\ & \hspace{1cm} \text{donde}\; K_\kappa\; \text{es la funcin Bessel modeificada de orden}\; \kappa. \end{align*}\]

The Mat'ern family (Matrn 1986) is the most commonly used class of semivariogram functions, where the parameter \(\kappa\) is the order of the function and controls the roughnesss of the process. More information about the Mat'ern family can be found in Handcock and Stein (1993), and in general about semivariogram functions in Diggle and Ribeiro (2007).

In the previous functions, \(\tau^2 > 0\) represents the semivariance between observations when \(h \rightarrow 0\), commonly known as nugget effect, and it can be the consequence of a discontinuity in the process, or of error in the measurements, or of both simultaneously:

\[\begin{align*} \gamma(0)=\tau^2. \end{align*}\]

In certain applications, might not be a nugget effect, then:

\[\begin{align*} \gamma(0)= 0. \end{align*}\]

The correlation between pairs of observations separated by large distances eventually disappears, which implies that their semivariance is equal to \(\sigma^2\), which is indeed the variance of an observation:

\[\begin{align*} \underset{h \rightarrow \infty}{\mathrm{lim}} \gamma(h)= \sigma^2. \end{align*}\]

That \(\sigma^2\) is known as the sill of the semivariogram.

The semivariogram can reach the sill for a certain distance \(h\), which represents the distance where the correlation disappears, or it can asymptotically approach the sill. In the previous semivariogram family functions, the parameter \(\phi\) represents the distance where the semivariance reaches 95% of the sill and is called the affective range. This parameter \(\phi\) represents the rate of decay of the correlation as a function of the distance, which controls the smoothness or wigglyness of the spatial variability of the predictions. The larger the effective range \(\phi\), the higher the spatial correlation and, therefore, the smoother the spatial variability of the predictions (smoother predictive functions). On the other hand, the smaller the \(\phi\), the lower the spatial correlation and, therefore, the more wiggly the spatial variability of the predictions (more wiggly predictive functions).

Figure 4.1 shows a standard model for the semivariogram and the covariogram jointly with their characteristic parameters: nugget (\(\tau^2\)), sill (\(\sigma^2\)) and effective range (\(\phi\)). And Figure 4.2 shows schematically the most common families for the semivariogram functions written above. (Muoz Viera 2012)

Figure 4.1: Standard models for the semivariogram and covariogram and their characteristic parameters. *Source: Muoz Viera 2012

Figure 4.2: Models for the semivariogram. *Source: Muoz Viera 2012

The estimation of the characteristic parameters of the semivariogram function from the sample data can be carried out by using standard optimization methods for functions, such as least square, generalized least square or maximun likelihood (Cressie and Hawkins 1980; Kitanidis 1983).

5.2 Study area

The study area corresponds to the Valencian Community (CV), Spain, and its surroundings, which is a Mediterranean coastal zone located in eastern Spain with an area of 23,255 Km2. It contains a mountainous area where the highest altitudes are about 1800 m. There exists a littoral plain region, principally constituted by floodplains and alluvial fans, and a coastline formed by smooth beaches and coastal lagoons.

5.2.1 Borders of the Valencian Community

The boundaries of the CV are provided by the shape file cv, and by using the R command readOGR it can be converted to the spatial-polygons R-object lim_cv (Bivand et al. 2008).

getwd()
lim_cv <- readOGR(dsn="Datos_cp4", layer="cv")

For more details about the structure and content of this spatial-polygons R-object lim_cv see the R-notebook Precipitation mapping using kriging techniques: Descriptive analysis and linear regression.

In Figure ??, the borders of the CV are plotted superimposed to a elevation map of the area. It consists in a multipolygon with two single polygons that draw the borders of the CV.

5.3 Data set

5.3.1 Elevation map

A elevation map of the CV and its surroundings is provided by a raster file, and by means of the R command raster it is converted to the raster R-object ras.

ras <- raster("Datos_cp4/mde_100.tif", values=TRUE)

For more details about the structure and content of this raster R-object ras see the R-notebook Precipitation mapping using kriging techniques: Descriptive analysis and linear regression.

5.3.2 Observational precipitation variables and input variables

The observational data set consists in precipitation observations and associated attributes of the observed locations as the spatial coordinates and the elevation. Thus, data set contains mean precipitation data for the period of 1960-2005 in 212 meteorological stations of the CV. Our study considers seasonal temporal scales. Thus, monthly rainfall means were grouped into the following variables: spring (spring: March, April, May), summer (summer: June, July, August), autumn (autumn: September, October, November), and winter (winter: December, January, February). annual contains the mean annual precipitation in each meteorological observatory.

The precipitation variables as well as the spatial coordinates and the elevation of the observed points are provided by a shape file. The spatial coordinates and the elevation are considered the input variables. The points shape file precip_seasonal which contains these data is read and converted to the spatial-points R-object dat by using the command readOGR.

dat <- readOGR(dsn="Datos_cp4", layer="precip_seasonal", integer64="warn.loss")
str(dat)

For more details about the structure and content of this spatial-points R-object dat as well as the histograms and descriptive statistics of the precipitation and input variables see the R-notebook Precipitation mapping using kriging techniques: Descriptive analysis and linear regression.

In Figure 5.1 the spring precipitation at the observed loactions, the elevation map of the CV and the borders of the CV are mapped.

# plot settings (see help(par))
# par(mfrow=c(1,2), mar=c(3.7, 4.1, 2.1, 1.1), mgp=c(1.8,0.6,0))

plot(dat@coords[ ,1:2], type="n", xlim=c(600000,900000), xlab="X", ylab="Y") # plot frame

image(ras, add=TRUE, col=terrain.colors(70, alpha=1)[70:1]) # adding the altitude map

# plotting the spring precipitation observations
q1 <- quantile(dat@data$spring, c(0,0.10,0.25,0.40,0.60,0.75,0.90,1))
br1 <- cut(dat@data$spring, breaks=q1, include.lowest=TRUE)
points(dat@coords[ ,1:2], type="p", col=brewer.pal(7,"Blues")[1:7][br1], asp=1, pch=16)

plot(lim_cv, add=TRUE) # adding the CV limits

# adding a legend for the spring observations
legend("bottomright", legend=levels(br1)[7:1], fill=brewer.pal(7,"Blues")[7:1], title= "Spring precipitation", cex=0.8, box.col = "grey", xpd = NA, bty = "n")

Figure 5.1: Map of the observed locations colored by the spring precipitation (left) and the elevation data (right).

5.3.3 Grid of predicting locations and predicting input variables

In order to obtain a continuous map of precipitation, we need to make punctual predictions in a dense grid of locations and have the input variables for these predicting locations. In R there are different ways to define a grid. In this case, we are going to use the raster R-object ras of the elvation map above obtained to construct the grid of predicting locations. The collection of pixel mid points make a grid itself, so we just have to extract the mid points and their x and y spatial coordinates of every pixel. As the raster R-object ras contains the elevation values of every location, then we directly have the three input variables needed: altitud and the spatial coordinates x and y.

In order to save computation, the spatial resolution of the raster object can be reduced, thus the number of points of the resulting grid will not be so large and further computation reduced. The command aggregate can be used for this pourpose, specifying a reduction factor. In this case we use a reduction factor of 1/16 (fact=c(4,4)).

ras <- aggregate(ras, fact=c(4,4), fun=mean)

Then, using the command rasterToPoints, the raster object ras can be converted to the SpatialPoints object loc and thus obtaning the grid of predicting locations, which already has the three input variables: altitud and the spatial coordinates x and y. The variable mde_100 in the slot data contains the altitud values of every location. The slot coords is a two-column matrix which also contains the two spatial coordinates x and Y of every locations.

loc <- rasterToPoints(ras, fun=NULL, spatial=TRUE)
str(loc)
## Formal class 'SpatialPointsDataFrame' [package "sp"] with 5 slots
##   ..@ data       :'data.frame':  601601 obs. of  1 variable:

Finally, the grid of predicting locations loc can be restricted to the study area by clipping it by the borders of CV. The command crop can be used for this purpose.

loc <- crop(loc, lim_cv)

5.4 Isotropic (omnidirectional) semivariogram with global tendency.

5.4.1 Scale and center the spatial coordinates

Using the library geoR to peformm kriging, a numerical inestability error is obtained when data have UTM spatial coordinates. Therefore, we have to make the computations, the semivariogram and the kriging predictions, using scaled spatial coordinates.

media <- colMeans(loc@coords[,]) # Centroid of the object 'loc'
desv <- sd(loc@coords[,]) # Common standard deviation of X and Y coordinates.

Scaling the observations

dat@coords <- scale(dat@coords, center= media, scale= c(desv,desv))

Scaling the predicting locations

loc@coords <- scale(loc@coords, center= media, scale= c(desv,desv))

5.4.2 Semivariogram for the whole spatial distance domain.

hist(distancias[distancias<=340000/desv], breaks=seq(0,340000,10000)/desv, main="", xlab="scaled distance / real distance (m)", xaxt="n", mgp=c(3.3, 1, 0))

axis(1, at= seq(0,340000,10000)/desv, labels= round(seq(0,340000,10000)/desv,2), tick= TRUE, mgp=c(3, 0, 1))

svar.mat12 <- variofit(vario=svar2, ini=c(sill, range), cov.model='matern', fix.nugget=FALSE, nugget=130, fix.kappa=TRUE, kappa=0.5, weights='cressie', minimisation.function='optim')

5.5 Kriging prediction

5.5.1 Kriging prediction

Adjustment of Kriging model

## krige.conv: Kriging performed using global neighbourhood

Adding kriging outcomes to the object loc

loc@data$predict <- uk$predict  # predictions
loc@data$predict.sd <- sqrt(uk$krige.var)  # prediction error

5.5.2 Cross-validation (CV) model assesment

for(i in 1:212){
uk_vc <- krige.conv(data= dat@data$spring[-i], coords= dat@coords[-i,], locations= dat@coords[i,], borders= NULL, krige= krige.control(type.krige= "ok", trend.d= trend.spatial( ~dat@coords[-i,1]*dat@coords[-i,2]*dat@data$ALTITUD[-i]), trend.l= trend.spatial( ~dat@coords[i,1]*dat@coords[i,2]*dat@data$ALTITUD[i]), obj.model= svar.mat32))

dat@data$predict.cv[i] <- uk_vc$predict
dat@data$predict.cv.sd[i] <- sqrt(uk_vc$krige.var)
}

dat@data$res.cv <- dat@data$spring[] - dat@data$predict.cv
